title: For Sale/Trade:  1955 Springfield Armory Garand with 5 En Bloc Clips
postcontent: This is an absolutely beautiful 1955 Springfield (SA) Armory M1 Garand; the rifle that General George S. Patton referred to as: " the greatest battlefield implement ever devised." She was originally purchased through the Civilian Marksmanship Program years ago. The rifle is chambered in the venerable 30-06 cartridge. The SA barrel dates to 4-55. The SA rifle serial number dates to 1955 as well. That, along with like condition and Patina, suggests the barrel is original to the gun. The serial number will be given upon phone conversation only. There are no visible import marks. The stainless gas seal is the only area exhibiting any significant wear. Rust is non-existent, nor are there any signs of major battle scars. Normal wear is minimal for the time frame. There is evidence of a faint ordnance cartouche stamp on the stock just below the left side of receiver.  The barrel is shiny and remains accurate. The rifle functions wonderfully and is accompanied by 5 en bloc clips.  The rifle wears an OD nylon sling, befitting of the time period in both use and appearance. The weapon has the normal matching of the major US manufacturers parts of that time:Receiver- SABarrel- 4-1955Trigger Group- International Harvester Op Rod- SA Bolt- Harrington and RichardsonSights (SA). The sights are in excellent mechanical condition and show minimal wear. They remain audible, tactile and precise on the firing line.This Garand is an excellent example of American Ingenuity. It retains the history of " the greatest generation", and will continue to be a legacy for generations to admire.*Numerous additional photos upon request.

title: For Sale:  Historically Significant Colt Model 3 1/2 Single action Revolver 1871
postcontent: For Sale I have a Colt Model 3 1/2 in .38 Rimfire. These Revolvers are Historically Significant as they represent Colts first Metallic Cartridge Revolver and their move away from percussion revolvers. These were manufactured from leftover percussion parts with a new cylinder and barrel. These revolvers are not often seen and when they are they usually command $1500 and up with no finish. Barrel length is 3 1/2" hence the model name 3 1/2. This one isn't the prettiest as it has some deep pitting on the barrel and cylinder but it functions like new and has a great bore. I have shot it with black powder .38 Rimfire and it functioned flawlessly. The wedge screw is broken and frozen in place and the wedge is frozen as well but I'm sure it could be removed with a good soak and some elbow grease as I only tapped in it slightly to try and remove it and it wouldn't budge. The grips also have a crack running the length of them but it is solid and not going anywhere. Cylinder scene is visable in place and barrel address is readable. So here is your chance to get Colts first single action made in 1872 before the first single action armies were produced in 1873. As an antique manufactured in 1872 I can ship this directly to your home with no restrictions. If shipping is required I would prefer payment by PayPal gift or send money to family and friends option with no mention of anything gun related aspaypal is very anti gun. I would also accept cashiers checks or money orders. Email, call, or text REDACTED.
